In both poems, feelings of loss are presented as having a strong impact on people. In ‘Cousin
Kate’, the repetition of “Why” in the ﬁrst stanza and “If” in the penultimate stanza conveys how the
speaker has started to obsess over her loss and wonders if her fate could have been avoided. .
In contrast, the speakers in ‘What Were They Like?’ are trying to ﬁnd a past that has been lost. The
ﬁrst speaker’s questions show their interest in what Vietnamese life was like. The second speaker tries
to answer the questions, but can only use what “was reported” as the loss of the Vietnamese culture
has left them uncertain. .
Answer Extract 2
Both poems use form to help illustrate the effects of loss on their subjects. The ballad form
of ‘Cousin Kate’ consists of alternate rhyme (e.g. ABCBDBEB) and alternating line lengths (8 and 6
syllables). This mimics the speaker’s thoughts, speciﬁcally how the memory of her abandonment keeps
returning to her and how she is unable to move on from her loss. . In contrast, ‘What Were They
Like?’ is divided into a free verse question and answer form that has uneven line lengths. The split in
the poem between questions and answers highlights the difference between the idealised perception of
the past and the harsh reality of the present. .
Answer Extract 3
The speakers in ‘Cousin Kate’ and ‘What Were They Like?’ experience very different types of
loss. One is a deeply personal loss, while the other is the broader loss of an entire culture. Rossetti’s
speaker emphasises how the loss is intensely personal through phrases such as “my heart”, and
“my love”, as the possessive determiner “my” immediately makes the speaker’s narrative seem more
private and intimate.
. In contrast, it is the lack of individual detail that makes the loss of human
life in ‘What Were They Like?’ so poignant. By using only plural nouns, such as “people”, “children”,
“fathers” and “sons”, the extensive scale of the loss is realised — there were so many deaths that
paying individual attention to each victim is impossible. .
